		<div class="comment_text"><p>If I could make a suggestion, having one code sample (however cool) is like only having one Resume. If you're pitching a small shop that needs an all rounder, you need to throw in something that works end to end with CSS and HTML. If the person who makes the hiring decsion is into OO, show Java integration, if they're into "cool stuff", show them something pretty in Flex 2. If they want you to maintain CF 5, show what you can do with tha. If they could also do with some help in the Kitchen, cook them breakfast one day!</p><p>Start by figuring out your ideal job and put together code samples for those, but if (say) you love back end but are open to an all rounder postion (I don't know what the job market is like in London right now), make sure to show some end to end solutions.</p><p>Oh, and if they have are committed to framework that you know, may be worth tweaking a sample to run on that framework so they know the learning curve won't be too steep.</p><p>Ray and I are probably into the same kind of programmers, but that doesn't mean the people hiring you will be looking for that!</p><p>Best Wishes,<br>Peter</p></div>
