		Comment <a href="#c_1713657074">13</a> by Tony Petruzzi
		posted on 9/4/2006 at 4:40 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>In the past I use to have some OSS applications that I wrote on my web site. If someone wanted code samples I would just tell them to download them from the web site and go poking around.</p><p>Nowadays since I only work on private projects, it's kinda hard for me to do such a thing. What I do do though is ask the client if I may include the code and web site as part of my profolio. Some say yes, a lot say no and I understand the reason.</p><p>I once had a company want the source code for <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2FRolist.com%3AUwMWbYtsjVquKL6kCVlzpEWTzUY&amp;cuid=3321886" rel="nofollow noopener" title="Rolist.com">Rolist.com</a> for the submission of sample code. My brother would only let me submit the code if I brought it the person on my laptop and the guy had to sign a form (basically a combo of an NDA and non-compete) before he saw it. Needless to say, once I told them the terms, they wanted me to show them the code without signing and I told them I'll pass on the job.</p></div>
