	<div>
		<div class="comment_header">
		Comment <a href="#c_1713657071">14</a> by Matthew
		posted on 9/5/2006 at 11:43 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Ray, I think you've hit the nail on the head.</p><p>I know that when I interview a candidate, there is no way I can guarantee the samples brought in are the candidate's actual work. That's OK. I ask candidates to bring in "the code you are most proud of". I don't care about the code at all, as I've hired candidates with rather paltry samples. I'm looking for the pride. A good candidate gets excited when talking about his work, a little (emphasis on little) defensive when changes are suggested, and quick to incorporate and elaborate on bug fixes or improvements.</p><p>If I want to test the candidate's coding skill, I'll propose a problem (generally one that the company is actually working on) and ask him to talk through his solution with me. I know he probably won't come up with anything approaching usable code, but I get to see how he thinks and attacks a problem. I like this 'conversational' method because it is easy to flesh out his experience by moving the discussion in other directions without it feeling like a test.</p><p>I also agree with Sean, coding under pressure is not a Good Thing. I set aside a reasonable amount of time at the beginning of the interview to make the candidate comfortable. This generally only takes a few minutes. I simply ask him questions about his interests. It generally doesn't take long for him to get excited, and at that point, stress just bleeds off. I also assure the candidate immediately after sitting down that I understand interviews can be stressful, and I'm not judging him on his interview skills, "I just want to see what you are passionate about, and how you tackle problems".</p><p>The last, and possibly most important, question is "how do you feel about 80's music?"</p></div>
